@node "EINLEITUNG" "About the program"
@next "INSTALATION"
@prev "DANK"

  This program can be used to decode and create Morse signals, especially for use in
  radio transmissions.

  Morse signals may be sampled and decoded using a soundsampler connected to the
  parallel port. Digital software filters are available for this purpose, but you
  can also add hardware filters at any time.

  Apart from that, the internal transmitter may be connected to the internal
  decoder for testing.

  This programs' status is currently experimental. The possibilities of the digital
  signal processing are limited.

  If enough people show interest in TUMID, I'll think about major extensions to the
  application. So, if you want more power, register or at least tell me that you
  are interested!

  TUMID was developed using GNU C++ and is based on my own class library.
   
@endnode

@node "INSTALLATION" "Program installation"
@next "PROGRAMMSTART"
@prev "EINLEITUNG"

  The installation of T.U.M.ID. is easy. The program needs several external
  @{"files" link "PROGRAMMTEILE" 0}, however it will find these automatically.
  All you have to do is copy the programs' drawer to the place you like.
  @{b}You won't need any assigns or other stupid path dependend things!@{ub}

  @{u}Notice:@{uu} The files and drawers found in the program directory may not be
  modified or deleted!

@endnode

@node "HILFE" "Getting help"
@next "VERSIONEN"
@prev "PROGRAMMSTART"

  In case you are running into problems: T.U.M.ID. offers you two ways to get help.

  First the short help, a fast, one-line help that gives a hint on the function
  of all windows and gadgets. Apart from that there is also the hyperhelp system
  based on this AmigaGuide document that gives you an extended description on
  all windows, gadgets and menus.

  The short help is build into the program and is always active. @{b}If you move
  the pointer over an active window or a gadget of an active window you'll see a
  short description of that item in the title of the screen.@{ub}

  If that isn't enough you can query the hyperhelp. @{b}Again move the pointer
  over the item of your interest and press the <Help>-key. The respective page
  of this document will be displayed.@{ub}

  If you don't want to see a specific page you can also use the <Guide>-gadget
  in the @{"main window" link "NID_MainWindow" 0}. It will open the main contents
  page of this document.
  
@endnode

@node "PROGRAMMSTART" "Starting the program"
@next "HILFE"
@prev "INSTALLATION"

  @{b}T.U.M.ID. may be started from both the Workbench and the CLI.@{ub}

  There are no Workbench-tooltypes or CLI arguments needed.

  If something went wrong T.U.M.ID. will of course notify you of this, however
  if you didn't modify any of the files or paths you shouldn't run into any
  serious problems.
  
@endnode

@node "VERSIONEN" "Program history"
@next "FUTURE"
@prev "HILFE"
        
  @{b}@{fg shine}T.U.M.ID.@{ub}@{fg text}

  @{u}Version 1.00@{uu}
    - First public release.
    
@endnode

@node "FUTURE" "Planned extensions"
@next "PROGRAMMTEILE"
@prev "VERSIONEN"

  First of all I must admit that I cannot guarantee any further development
  of this program.
  Notice: This heavily depends on new registrations.

  @{u}The following modifications and extensions are planned:@{uu}

  - A WarpUp PPC version.

  - General optimizations.

  - Extension of the digital signal processing.

  - More signal sources and sinks.

@endnode

