@node "DEVELOPE" "Developer infos"
@next "FENSTER"
@prev "PROGRAMMTEILE"

  There are no informations available for developers in the current version.

@endnode

@node "FENSTER" "The various windows"
@next "NID_MainWindow"
@prev "DEVELOPE"

  The application uses several windows, each covering specific functions. All can
  be closed by either pressing the close gadget or using the <Esc>-key and opened
  by the respective button in the @{"main window" link "NID_MainWindow" 0}.
  One exception is the @{"main window" link "NID_MainWindow" 0} itself. Closing this one means leaving TUMID.

  The <Tab>-key activates the first text or numeric gadget of the active window.

  Most of the functions that you can see in the windows are also available as a
  menu item and therefore also have a shortcut (which you can lookup in the menu).
  Additional keyboard shortcuts (e.g. cursor keys) are described in the docs of
  the corresponding windows.

  @{u}More information about these windows:@{uu}

  @{" Main window              " link "NID_MainWindow" 0}
  @{" Configuration window     " link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0}

  @{" Sender window            " link "NID_TraWindow" 0}
  @{" Sender configuration     " link "NID_TraCfgWindow" 0}

  @{" Receiver window          " link "NID_RecWindow" 0}
  @{" Receiver configuration   " link "NID_RecCfgWindow" 0}


  @{" List selection requester " link "NID_GetItemWindow" 0}

@endnode

@node "NID_MainWindow" "The main window and its contents"
@next "NID_PortWindow"
@prev "FENSTER"

  The main window is of course the most important one. It controls all other
  windows of the application.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets and displays here:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight} Program  @{fg text}
  @{" About       " link "NID_MainAbout" 0}
  @{" Config      " link "NID_MainConfig" 0}
  @{" Iconify     " link "NID_MainIconify" 0}
  @{" Guide       " link "NID_MainGuide" 0}
  @{" Quit        " link "NID_MainQuit" 0}

  @{fg highlight} Receiver @{fg text}
  @{" Config      " link "NID_MainRecCfg" 0}
  @{" Open        " link "NID_MainRecWin" 0}

  @{fg highlight} Transmitter    @{fg text}
  @{" Config      " link "NID_MainTraCfg" 0}
  @{" Open        " link "NID_MainTraWin" 0}

  @{fg highlight} Clock       @{fg text}
  @{" Time        " link "NID_MainTimeC" 0}
  @{" Date        " link "NID_MainDateC" 0}
  @{" Weekday     " link "NID_MainWeekdayC" 0}

  If a window is already open you can activate and push it to the front by
  pressing the respective gadget.
  
@endnode

@node "NID_MainAbout" "Main window / Program / About"

  This gadget opens an info requester that contains some short informations
  about the application and if it's @{"registered" link "REGISTER" 0} or not.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainConfig" "Main window / Program / Config"

  This gadget opens the @{"configuration window" link "NID_ConfigWindow" 0}.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainIconify" "Main Window/ Program / Iconify"

  This gadget closes all windows and the screen - the program goes into
  stand-by mode. You can reopen the user interface by double-clicking on
  the icon that appears on the Workbench.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainGuide" "Main window / Program / Guide"

  Opens the @{"contents page" link "MAIN" 0} of this guide.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainQuit" "Main window / Program / Quit"

  You can leave T.U.M.ID. by pressing this gadget. A requester will pop up and
  ask if you really want to leave this fine application.
@endnode

@node "NID_MainRecCfg" "Main window / Receiver / Open"

  Opens the @{"receiver configuration window" link "NID_RecCfgWindow" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_MainRecWin" "Main window / Receiver / Open"

  Opens the @{"receiver window" link "NID_RecWindow" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_MainTraCfg" "Main window / Transmitter / Config"

  Opens the @{"transmitter configuration window" link "NID_TraCfgWindow" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_MainTraWin" "Main window / Transmitter / Open"

  Opens the @{"transmitter window" link "NID_TraWindow" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_MainTimeC" "Main window / Clock / Time"

  You can see the current time here.
@endnode
@node "NID_MainDateC" "Main window / Clock / Date"

  You can see the current date here.
@endnode
@node "NID_MainWeekdayC" "Main window / Clock / Weekday"

  You can see the current weekday here.
@endnode

@node "NID_SystemGadget" "System gadgets"

  This is a system gadget, created by the operating system. Please have a
  look at your AmigaOS manual for its function.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigWindow" "The configuration window"

  The configuration window has two important functions. It features some
  global options that affect the whole application and it lets the user
  save or load them as well as the current settings of the main window
  and itself.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets and displays here:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}  Optionen  @{fg text}

  @{" Screenmode                          " link "NID_ConfigScreen" 0} @{" ? " link "NID_ConfigScreenSel" 0}
  @{" Printer                             " link "NID_ConfigPrinter" 0} @{" ? " link "NID_ConfigPrinterSel" 0}
                                @{" Small-Help " link "NID_ConfigSmallHelp" 0}
                  @{"Screenmode like Workbench " link "NID_ConfigLikeWB" 0}

  @{"   Default   " link "NID_ConfigDefault" 0}  @{"    Save    " link "NID_ConfigSave" 0}  @{"   Load    " link "NID_ConfigLoad" 0}

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigScreen" "Configuration window / Options / Screenmode"

  This is the currently used screen mode.
@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigPrinter" "Configuration window / Options / Printer"

  This is the device that T.U.M.ID. uses to print data. Usually this is the
  systems' "printer.device" or something compatible.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigDefault" "Configuration window / Gadgets / Default"

  The global settings and the settings of the configuration window will be
  reset to the defaults.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigSaveAll" "Configuration window / Gadgets / Save"

  The current configuration of the various windows can be saved here.

  A @{"window selection requester" link "NID_WinSelectWindow" 0} will be opened which lets you
  select the window in question.

  Note: Only the parent windows are shown! If you want to save the settings
        of a specific window, this will also happen for all its child windows!

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigSave" "Configuration window / Gadgets / Save"

  The global settings and the settings of the configuration window will be saved.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigLoad" "Configuration window / Gadgets / Load"

  The global settings and the settings of the configuration window will be loaded.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigScreenSel" "Configuration window / Options / Screenmode <?>"

  Lets you select a screen mode.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigPrinterSel" "Configuration window / Options / Printer <?>"

  Lets you select a printer device.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigSmallHelp" "Configuration window / Options / Small-Help"

  Here you can enable or disable the @{"small help" link "HILFE" 0}. If enabled, short info
  texts will be dispayed in the screens' title bar for every window or gadget.

@endnode

@node "NID_ConfigLikeWB" "Configuration window / Options / "

  The application does not choose its own screen mode but clones the one
  of the Workbench instead.

@endnode

@node "NID_GetItemWindow" "The list selection requester"

  The list selection requester is used to select an item from a list. In this
  application it is used to let the user select a text.

  If open, the requester locks the rest of the user interface.

  In the requester window you can, in addition to the usual shortcuts, use the
  following keys:

  <Cursor up>             Select previous item.
  <Cursor down>           Select next item.
  <Shift>+<Cursor up>     Select first item.
  <Shift>+<Cursor down>   Select last item.
  <Enter>                 Accept the selected items (sames as the @{" OK-gadget " link "NID_GetItemOk" 0})

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets and displays here:@{uu}

  @{"           List          " link "NID_GetItemItems" 0}
  @{"     OK     " link "NID_GetItemOk" 0} @{" Cancel " link "NID_GetItemCancel" 0}

@endnode

@node "NID_GetItemItems" "List selection requester / List"

  In this list you can see all texts that are available. Double-clicking
  one of the items is the same as clicking on the  @{" OK-gadget " link "NID_GetItemOk" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_GetItemCancel" "List selection requester / Cancel"

  Cancels the requester. The requester will be closed and nothing will be done.

@endnode

@node "NID_GetItemOk" "List selection requester / Ok"

  Accept the selected items and use them.

@endnode



@node "NID_RecWindow" "The receiver window"

  The receiver window is used to receive and decode Morse signals. According to
  the settings in the @{"receiver configuration window" link "NID_RecCfgWindow" 0} this window
  opens the @{"signal source" link "NID_RecCfgSigSource" 0} and digitizes all incoming
  signals. They are filtered using various algorythms.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets and displays here:@{uu}


  @{fg highlight}Log@{fg text}

  @{" Log                                                   " link "NID_RecLog" 0}
  @{"  Enable  " link "NID_RecEnableLog" 0}@{"  Save  " link "NID_RecSaveLog" 0}@{"  Print  " link "NID_RecPrintLog" 0}@{"  Clear  " link "NID_RecClearLog" 0}@{"  Copy  " link "NID_RecCopyLog" 0}@{"  Send  " link "NID_RecSendLog" 0}

  @{" Receiver display                                    " link "NID_RecRecLine" 0}@{"ON" link "NID_RecReceive" 0}

@endnode

@node "NID_RecLog" "Receiver window / Log"

  The log of the received signals. All received data is displayed here if this
  function has been enabled using the @{"Log/Enabled" link "NID_RecEnableLog" 0} checkbox.
  Please also have a look at the description of the @{"receiver display" link "NID_RecRecLine" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecEnableLog" "Receiver window / Log / Enabled"

  Activate the @{"log display" link "NID_RecLog" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecRecLine" "Receiver window / Log / Receiver display"

  Here you can see the decoded text that is currently received. A number sign ('#')
  represents a sign that TUMID was not able to decode.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecSaveLog" "Receiver window / Log / Save"

  Save the current contents of the @{"receiver log" link "NID_RecLog" 0}. You can
  select the filename in a requester.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecPrintLog" "Receiver window / Log / Print"

  Print the current contents of the @{"receiver log" link "NID_RecLog" 0} using
  the selected @{"printer device" link "NID_ConfigPrinter" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecClearLog" "Receiver window / Log / Clear"

  Deletes the current contents of the @{"receiver log" link "NID_RecLog" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCopyLog" "Receiver window / Log / Copy"

  Copies the current contents of the @{"receiver log" link "NID_RecLog" 0} to unit 0
  of the cliboard. After that you can e.g. insert it into a word processing application.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecSendLog" "Receiver window / Log / Send"

  Transmit the current contents of the @{"receiver log" link "NID_RecLog" 0} via
  the @{"transmitter window" link "NID_TraWindow" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecReceive" "Receiver window / Log / ON"

  Activate the receiver. Only if this switch is set to on will the receiver
  scan the signal source and decodes the received signals.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCfgWindow" "The receiver configuration window"

  The receiver configuration window is used to control the behaviour of the
  receiver window. You can save the receiver options and the configuration of
  the receiver window.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets here:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}receiver options@{fg text}

  @{" Signal source    " link "NID_RecCfgSigSource" 0}
  @{" Signal frequency " link "NID_RecCfgFreq" 0}
  @{" Threshold        " link "NID_RecCfgTresh" 0}
  @{" DID/DAH filter   " link "NID_RecCfgFIRPRec" 0}


  @{fg highlight}Receiver configuration@{fg text}

  @{" Default " link "NID_RecCfgDefault" 0}@{" Save " link "NID_RecCfgSave" 0}@{" Load " link "NID_RecCfgLoad" 0}

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCfgSigSource" "Receiver configuration / Receiver options / Signal source"

  Here the signal source that is used by the @{"receiver window" link "NID_RecWindow" 0}
  is set. There are currently two possible sources:

  - Internal transmitter
    The internal transmitter is especially useful for testing purposes. The @{"transmitter window" link "NID_TraWindow" 0}
    will be connected to the @{"receiver window" link "NID_RecWindow" 0} internally and an
    analogue transmitter is simulated.

  - TT2 parallel sampler
    The most important setting. Here a Techno-Sound-Turbo II-compatible 8-bit digitzer
    connected to the Amigas' internal parallel interface is used as signal source.
    The left and right channels are added. Therefore it should in most cases be
    engough to connect only on channel to the radio equipment (or any other Morse
    source).

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCfgFreq" "Receiver configuration / Receiver options / Signal frequency"

  This is the frequency which is checked for Morse signals.
  If you are using the internal transmitter make sure that the @{"transmitter window" link "NID_TraWindow" 0}
  uses the same frequency as the receiver.

  Upon changes to the frequency setting the program will stop signal analysis for
  a short moment and recalculate the filter characteristics.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCfgTresh" "Receiver configuration / Receiver options / Threshold"

  This is the threshold value used to separate the Morse signals from the background
  noise after signal processing.

  The @{"receiver display" link "NID_RecRecLine" 0} is very important for finding the
  best threshold value.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCfgFIRPrec" "Receiver configuration / Receiver options / DID/DAH filter"

  This is the precision (or degree) of the internal, digital filters.
  The bigger this value is, the better will the background noise be separated
  from the signal. However, the computing power needed will also increase
  dramatically.
  If you own a small Amiga you should select the least availabe precision and
  instead use special hardware filters on the output of your signal source (which
  is obviously not possible if you use the internal TUMID-transmitter).

  Upon changes on the precision setting the application will shortly stop the
  signal analysis to re-calculate the filter characteristics.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCfgDefault" "Receiver configuration / Default"

  Reset the configuration of the receiver and its windows.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCfgSave" "Receiver configuration / Save"

  Save the configuration of the receiver and its windows.

@endnode

@node "NID_RecCfgLoad" "Receiver configuration / Load"

  Load the configuration of the receiver and its windows.

@endnode



@node "NID_TraCfgWindow" "The transmitter configuration window"

  The transmitter configuration window is used to control the behaviour of the
  @{"transmitter window" link "NID_TraWindow" 0}. Here you can save and load
  the transmitter options and the configuration of the transmitter window.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets here:@{uu}

  @{fg highlight}Transmitter options@{fg text}

  @{" Signal drain     " link "NID_TraCfgSigDrain" 0}
  @{" Signal frequency " link "NID_TraCfgDDFreq" 0}
  @{" Signal amplitude " link "NID_TraCfgDDAmpl" 0}
  @{" Break frequency  " link "NID_TraCfgRFreq" 0}
  @{" Break amplitude  " link "NID_TraCfgRAmpl" 0}
  @{" DID length       " link "NID_TraCfgDidLen" 0}
  @{" ID name          " link "NID_TraCfgID" 0}
  @{" Edit sequences   " link "NID_TraCfgEDSeq" 0}


  @{fg highlight}Transmitter configuration@{fg text}

  @{" Default " link "NID_TraCfgDefault" 0}@{" Save " link "NID_TraCfgSave" 0}@{" Load " link "NID_TraCfgLoad" 0}


@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgSigDrain" "Transmitter configuration / Transmitter options / Signal drain"

  This is the configuration for the so called signal drain of the transmitter.
  Here you can define how the transmitter should send Morse signals.

  Currently ony the setting "AmigaOS Audio" is available here, i.e. the internal
  Amiga audio hardware is used to output the signals. To broadcast them, simply
  connect Audio Out of your Amiga to a compatible input of your transmitter.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgDDFreq" "Transmitter configuration / Transmitter options / Signal frequency"

  The signal frequency (in Hertz) used for DIDs and DAHs.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgDDAmpl" "Transmitter configuration / Transmitter options / Signal amplitude"

  The signal amplitude used for the Morse signals.
  If used with the AmigaOS-Audio-@{"drain" link "NID_TraCfgSigDrain" 0} the amplitude
  setting this is the same as the volume of the Morse signal.

  This should be left at 100%.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgRFreq" "Transmitter configuration / Transmitter options / Break frequency"

  The frequency of the sound that is send within the breaks between the
  DIDs and DAHs. This is usually not necessary, but might be useful
  for some experiments.

  To disable this feature you just need to set @{"break amplitude" link "NID_TraCfgRAmpl" 0} to 0%.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgRAmpl" "Transmitter configuration / Transmitter options / Break amplitude"

  This is the volume of the sound that is send within the breaks between the
  DIDs and DAHs. This should be left at 0% normally.

  See also: @{"break frequency" link "NID_TraCfgRFreq" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgDidLen" "Transmitter configuration / Transmitter options / DID lengths"

  The duration of a Morse dot (a so called "DID") in milliseconds.

  All other components of the Morse signal, the dashes (DAH) and the various
  breaks, are calculated based on this value.

   - dash length (DAH)           = 3 * DID
   - break between DIDs and DAHs = 1 * DID
   - break between two letters   = 3 * DID
   - break between two words     = 7 * DID

  These factors are currently build into the application and therefore cannot
  be modified.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgEDSeq" "Transmitter configuration / Transmitter options / Sequenzeditor"

  This button opens the @{"sequence editor" link "NID_SeEdWindow" 0}. In this editor you
  can create and store your own texts (signal sequences).

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgID" "Transmitter configuration / Transmitter options / ID Name"

  This is the name of the user or the station. This text can be transmitted using
  the @{"ID-button" link "NID_TraIDTra" 0} in the @{"transmitter window" link "NID_TraWindow" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgDefault" "Transmitter configuration / Vorgaben"

  Reset the configuration of the transmitter and its windows to the default settings.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgSave" "Transmitter configuration / Sichern"

  Save the configuration of the transmitter and its windows.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraCfgLoad" "Transmitter configuration / Load"

  Load the configuration of the transmitter and its windows.

@endnode



@node "NID_TraWindow" "The transmitter window"

  The transmitter window is used to send automatically encoded Morse signals.
  According to the settings in the @{"transmitter configuration window" link "NID_TraCfgWindow" 0}
  the transmitter window sends all text the user enters to the @{"signal drain" link "NID_TraCfgSigDrain" 0}.

  @{u}You can find the following gadgets here:@{uu}


  @{fg highlight}Log@{fg text}

  @{" Log                                         " link "NID_TraLog" 0}
  @{"  Enable  " link "NID_TraEnableLog" 0}@{"  Repeat  " link "NID_TraReapeatLog" 0}@{"  Save  " link "NID_TraSaveLog" 0}@{" Print " link "NID_TraPrintLog" 0}@{" Clear " link "NID_TraClearLog" 0}


  @{fg highlight}Send@{fg text}

  @{" Text                                    " link "NID_TraLineTra" 0}@{"BRK" link "NID_TraBreak" 0}
  @{"   File   " link "NID_TraFileTra" 0}@{"    ID    " link "NID_TraIDTra" 0}@{"  Sequence  " link "NID_TraSeqTra" 0}@{" Clipboard " link "NID_TraClipTra" 0}


@endnode

@node "NID_TraLog" "Transmitter window / Log"

  The transmitter log. All send data is displayed here if the log function is
  on (see @{"Log/Enabled" link "NID_TraEnableLog" 0}).
  Please see also the description on the @{"Transmit/Text-gadget" link "NID_TraLineTra" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraEnableLog" "Transmitter window / Log / Enabled"

  Enable the @{"transmitter log" link "NID_TraLog" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraRepeatLog" "Transmitter window / Log / Repeat"

  This gadget activates a special transmission mode. In this mode all other
  gadgets will be disabled and the contents of the log is send over and over.

  This function is especially useful if the same message should be send over
  a long time without requiring any user input.

  To create such a message, you`ll have to do the following:
   - Clear the log. (if not already empty).
   - Activate the log (if not already active).
   - Enter the message and send it once. It`ll then appear in the log.
   - Start the Log/Repeat mode.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraSaveLog" "Transmitter window / Log / Save"

  Save the current contents of the @{"transmitter log" link "NID_TraLog" 0} in a
  selectable textfile.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraPrintLog" "Transmitter window / Log / Print"

  Print the current contents of the @{"transmitter log" link "NID_TraLog" 0} using
  the selected @{"printer device" link "NID_ConfigPrinter" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraClearLog" "Transmitter window / Log / Clear"

  Clears the @{"transmitter log" link "NID_TraLog" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraLineTra" "Transmitter window / Transmit / Text"

  Here you can enter the text that you want to transmit. Transmission
  starts after pressing Return.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraBreak" "Transmitter window / Transmit / BRK"

  Abort the current transmission.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraFileTra" "Transmitter window / Transmit / File"

  Lets you select an ASCII-textfile to transmit.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraIDTra" "Transmitter window / Transmit / ID"

  The user-defined @{"ID-name" link "NID_TraCfgID" 0} is transmitted.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraSeqTra" "Transmitter window / Transmit / Sequence"

  A @{"list selection requester" link "NID_GetItemWindow" 0} is opened where you
  can select one of the displayed text sequences to send.

  New sequences can be added in the @{"sequence editor" link "NID_SeEdWindow" 0}.
  This editor is available in the @{"transmitter configuration window" link "NID_TraCfgWindow" 0}.

@endnode

@node "NID_TraClipTra" "Transmitter window / Transmit / Clipboard"

  If there is some text in the clipboard (unit 0), it will be transmitted.

@endnode



@node "NID_SeEdWindow" "The sequence editor window"

  Using the sequence editor you can create and modify often used texts
  for the transmitter window. These can later on be send with only
  three clicks.

  In addition to the usual shortcuts you can use the following keys in
  this window:

  <Cursor up>            Select previous sequence
  <Cursor down>          Select next sequence
  <Shift>+<Cursor uo>    Select first sequence
  <Shift>+<Cursor down>  Select last sequence


  @{u}The window contains these gadgets:@{uu}

  @{"             Sequences            " link "NID_SeEdSeqs" 0}
  @{" Add " link "NID_SeEdAdd" 0} @{"  Delete  " link "NID_SeEdDel" 0} @{" Clear all " link "NID_SeEdClear" 0}

  @{"Name                              " link "NID_SeEdSeqName" 0}
  @{"Text                              " link "NID_SeEdSeqSeq" 0}

@endnode

@node "NID_SeEdSeqs" "Sequence editor / Sequences"

  The list of all available text sequences, alphabetically sorted.
  Only the sequence names are shown.

@endnode

@node "NID_SeEdAdd" "Sequence editor / Add new"

  Creates a new sequence and inserts it alphabetically sorted into the list.
  The new sequence will be selected automatically.

@endnode

@node "NID_SeEdDel" "Sequence editor / Delete"

  The selected sequence is removed from the list.

@endnode

@node "NID_SeEdClear" "Sequence editor / Clear all"

  Remove all sequences from the list.

@endnode

@node "NID_SeEdSeqName" "Sequence editor / Name"

  The name of the selected sequence. Use a short and descriptive name
  here to be able to distinguish between your sequences later on.

@endnode

@node "NID_SeEdSeqSeq" "Sequence editor / Text"

  This is the text that is transmitted by this sequence.

@endnode

